      "quickCheck": {
        "prompt": "A student earns an obtained standard score of 72 on a language processing test. The test manual reports a 95% confidence interval of plus or minus 5 points. The eligibility cutoff for the district is 70. A team member says, 'The score is 72, she doesn't qualify.' What should the team consider before making this determination?",
        "answer": "The team should consider the full confidence interval of 67 to 77. Because the student's true score could fall anywhere within that band, including below 70, an obtained score of 72 cannot responsibly be treated as definitively above the cutoff of 70. Ignoring the confidence interval when a score falls near a criterion is a fundamental misuse of norm-referenced data.",
        "hint": "Think about what it means when a confidence interval overlaps the eligibility cutoff; can the team treat the obtained score as a precise fact?"
      },
      "example": "An evaluation report states that a student's reading composite is 68 (95% CI: 63-73). The special educator explains to the team that while the obtained score is 68, measurement error means the student's true score could be as high as 73. This uncertainty matters most when the score falls near an eligibility threshold."
